lue="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gscho"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">School</CodeD><CodeI org="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="800035"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018592-20180327-145232"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Political/General News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gedu"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gptech"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gscho"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="glife"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Living/Lifestyle</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gptech"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">ST</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Apple's new entry-level iPad might be the way forward for education</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>CHICAGO - During the keynote in an media event held on Tuesday (March 27) in Chicago's Lane Technical College Prep High School, Apple's chief executive officer Tim Cook said: "We have been at this for 40 years and we care deeply about education."</Para><Para>And thus kicked off Apple's education-centric event, during which the tech giant announced a new entry-level 9.7-inch iPad. It is virtually the same iPad like last year's but now features a faster A10 processor and supports augmented reality (AR) apps, which can be great learning tools.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Another main feature is the support of Apple Pencil stylus, so students can draw or annotate on supported apps.</Para><Para>Apple also announced Schoolwork, a new app that helps teachers create assignments and see student progress. It features Handouts, which is an easy way to create and send assignments with almost any type of content, from web links to PDFs.</Para><Para>While many analysts have predicted a price cut for the iPad in order to make in-roads to the education market dominated by Google and Microsoft, Apple has retained the same pricing as the previous model starting from $498 for 32GB Wi-Fi model.</Para><Para>Apple does offer a slight discount for Singapore schools and students at $468 for the same model. The Apple Pencil ($138) is also available for an education discount of $125.</Para><Para>However, Chromebooks in Singapore can go as low as $309 for an Edxis Education Chromebook Lumos. And it comes with a keyboard, unlike the iPad.</Para><Para>As you might expect, instead of competing in pricing, Apple's strategy is about its holistic nature of its education offering - from hardware to software.</Para><Para>Apple's vice president of product marketing Greg Joswiak told The Straits Times that Apple is trying to do things differently that no one can match.</Para><Para>Mr Joswiak cited AR as one example, which browser-based apps found in Chromebooks cannot do.</Para><Para>In fact, unlike the usual hands-on sessions of such Apple events, the media (including myself) were brought from classroom to classroom to experience the various "lessons" taught by real educators.</Para><Para>The media was shown how a teacher can lock all the iPads in a classroom to prevent students from using them, or how a teacher can unlock just one app for students to use to prevent unnecessary multitasking.</Para><Para>We were also taught how to make clips, create animated presentations and how to code to make a UBTech robot dance. It was to give the media a first-hand experience on how Apple's education eco-system is going to work.</Para><Para>Personally, I think I will pay more attention in class and probably learn more, if there are all these fun activities using the iPad.</Para><Para>I have no idea how children are taught these days, since I have no kids. But I would think that by having an iPad in their hands, young children would be more excited to learn than staring at their textbooks.</Para><Para>From my understanding, e-learning has not really taken off in Singapore. Very few schools use Chromebooks even.</Para><Para>But the new entry-level iPad might be the game-changer. It is something kids love to have and certainly know how to use.</Para><Para>I know of parents who bought the iPad Pro, just so that their kids can draw using the Apple Pencil. But now, they no longer need to buy the expensive iPad Pro to do so. The new, more affordable iPad will do the trick.</Para><Para>That said, the main problem I foresee is still the price. Not all parents would be able to afford the iPad. And this is probably the biggest obstacle that Apple is going to face moving forward.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Trevor Tan </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contac